The amount of medication to be dispensed to the patient for each normal fill (excluding trial or other special first fills). Although CeRx does not have this as mandatory, since PIN uses this value, it should be specified if at all possible.

PIN will only use the Fill Quantity to determine the amount per fill. If it is not specified, PIN will not use the administration instructions and the Days Supply. Instead, it will not report Number of Fills Remaining in any query responses.
If true, indicates that the drug must be dispensed exactly as prescribed. PIN has constrained this to be fixed to the value "true".

annotation.text: CeRx defines this as 0..1 but the effective time is required in PIN so this is mandatory.
This identifier references an external allergy test. PIN will simply store this value for information purposes. No validation of the id will be made.

A code indicating result of the allergy test.
Because PIN is not using SNOMED, this attribute is mandatory.
This is a recording of a patient reaction that is believed to be associated with the allergy/intolerance.
Because PIN is not using SNOMED, this is fixed to RXNASSESS.
Because PIN is not using SNOMED, this is fixed to "RELATED"
A KEY204 error issue will be returned if this record identifier is not found in PIN.
This is the identifier of the record or order that caused the reaction. This could be for a prescription or other active medication records.

This will indicate whether this is a drug allergy, a non- drug allergy, a drug intolerance, or a non-drug intolerance. CODE_INVAL error issue will be returned if non- leaf-level codes are sent, i.e. OINT is not allowed while EALG is.
As SK does not implement record-level masking, this must be NORMAL or a CODE_INVAL error issue will be returned.
This can be 'N' or 'U'. CODE_INVAL error issue will be returned if not.

PIN is extending the IntoleranceValue vocabulary to include FDB Allergen Group Codes and will not accept the ClinicalDrug child domain vocabulary. Because PIN is not using SNOMED, this attribute is mandatory.
Indicates the type of agent that the patient was exposed to which caused the adverse reaction. This includes Drug, Food, Latex, Dust, etc. Send "UNK" if the material is unknown.
Because PIN is not using SNOMED, this is fixed to "DX".
Specifies the kind of reaction, as experienced by the patient. Because PIN does not support ADRs, this field is now mandatory.
Indicates the agent that is believed to have caused the allergic reaction.
Indicates the person suffering from the allergy/intolerance.
Indicates that the result set should be filtered to include only those allergy/intolerance records for the specified status.
If a non-leaf code is specified, then all records whose type is in the specified code\'s hierarchy will be returned. Example: if ALG is specified, any DALG, EALG, or FALG will be returned.
Indicates whether or not notes attached to the allergy/intolerance records are to be returned along with the detailed information.
This will be compared to the birthdate of the patient given by the ID. (See the External Registry ID section for details on the comparison and the error that may be raised.)
This will be compared to the gender of the patient given by the ID. (See the External Registry ID section for details on the comparison and the error that may be raised.)

Identifier of the patient who is the subject of the allergy/intolerance query. Filter the result set to include only those records pertaining to the patient with this ID. A KEY204 error issue will be returned if this ID does not exist in the jurisdictional client registry.

The name of the patient who is the subject of the allergy/intolerance query. This will be compared to the name of the patient given by the ID. (See the External Registry ID section on the comparison and the error that may be raised.)
A coded value denoting a specific reaction. E.g. Code for 'rash'. The result set will be filtered to include only those allergy records or intolerance records pertaining to the specified reaction.
This is the identifier of the allergy/intolerance record.
This will indicate whether this is a drug allergy, a non- drug allergy, a drug intolerance, or a non-drug intolerance.
A KEY204 error issue will be returned if this ID does exist in PIN.
Indicates the date on which the patient was born.
This will be compared to the birthdate of the patient given by the ID. (See the External Registry ID section for details on the comparison and the error that may be raised.)
This will be compared to the gender of the patient given by the ID. (See the External Registry ID section for details on the comparison and the error that may be raised.)
Indicates the gender (sex) of the patient.
A "KEY204" error issue will be returned if this ID does not exist in the jurisdiction\'s client registry.
Identifier of the patient who is the subject of the allergy/intolerance query. Filter the result set to include only those records pertaining to the patient with this ID.
This will be compared to the name of the patient given by the ID. (See the External Registry ID section for details on the comparison and the error that may be raised.)
The name of the patient who is the subject of the allergy/intolerance query.
Because PIN is not using SNOMED, this attribute is mandatory.
